# Patients put at risk by EU laws on working time, doctors warn

This article was published on guardian.co.uk at 09.58 GMT on Thursday 12
January 2012. It was last modified at 10.06 GMT on Thursday 12 January 2012.

![NHS hospital](http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-
images/Guardian/About/General/2012/1/12/1326362176564/NHS-hospital-006.jpg)

Senior doctors have warned that standards being reached by future consultants
are being undermined by EU laws. Photograph: David Sillitoe for the Guardian

Patients' safety is being put at risk because trainee doctors in the UK are
not getting enough on-the-job experience, leading doctors have warned.

The "stifling effect" of the European working time directive is limiting the
hours they work so much that the standards reached by future medical and
surgical consultants is being undermined, according to Norman Williams,
president of the Royal College of Surgeons, and Sir Richard Thompson,
president of the Royal College of Physicians.

In a letter to the Daily Telegraph, they also highlight concerns about
variations in training requirements in different EU member states and the
language skills of some doctors.

"It is also essential to ensure that doctors are competent," they say. "But
the existing EU legal framework fails to recognise that periodic revalidation
and requirements to participate in continuing professional development vary
significantly across member states.

"The increased mobility of health professionals in the EU has highlighted huge
variations both in the practical abilities of professionals of similar grades,
and in the systems set up to ensure quality, in different member states."

The doctors' letter adds: "We continue to be concerned about the future of
medical training – acute medical training, in particular – and the effect of
the European working time directive on acute medical and surgical trainees,
which reduces the number of hours available for them to train. We call for
flexibility at a European and a national level with regard to how on-call time
and compensatory rest for trainees are calculated."

The letter is likely to infuriate the European commission, which is already
proposing some changes to the rules governing free movement of labour within
the EU, partly in response to the storm that followed the Guardian's
revelations of similar concerns over patient safety raised by medical
regulators and GPs in 2009.

But many professional bodies in the UK do not think these go far enough.
Before Christmas, the General Medical Council (GMC), the regulator for
doctors, warned that EU doctors would still be able to register in the UK
without being tested on their English or medical competence.

The health secretary, Andrew Lansley, is strengthening the powers of NHS
employers to check on medics' language skills under measures not bound by EU
laws, but the GMC warned it would first have to recognise doctors'
qualifications without giving them the same checks that were applied when
doctors from other parts of the world sought work.

The commission says that existing EU rules, including on language skills, were
agreed by all member states and, if applied correctly, protect patients and do
not endanger their safety. Problems in some member states have been, or are
being, rectified by national systems without changes to EU law, it says.

However, the commission recognises the need to "clarify and slightly amend"
some aspects of EU rules and is now doing so.

